node.text:
Watch to learn how @beholdingeye captured his favorite photo on the Canon Road Trip.
 
"The lighting was optimal for shooting waterfalls in the gorge this day; mostly cloudy with filtered light. With these conditions, I used my 4 stop neutral density filter paired with a polarizing filter. Filters allow the photographer to achieve the desired effect they are envisioning. By using a neutral density filter I could increase my shutter speed to smooth out the water, and cut through the glare on top of the water at the same time.
 
Do you use filters to work around difficult light?“

node.title: Canon Road Trip: Photo Review with Paul Seibert

node.text: Find out what’s in #CanonExplorerOfLight @vanessajoy’s gear bag, or in this case gear closet! "After 20 years of accumulating photography gear, I was getting sick and tired of rearranging bags (and finding lost gear) for each type of shoot. I finally found the perfect solution in having a gear cabinet, instead of a gear bag. Now I can grab exactly what tools I need for the type of photoshoot I'm going on, without playing the 'which bag is my 50mm 1.2 in?' game. Best thing I've ever done!"

However, this is a popular pier and many other photographers had crowded in that desired spot. So this was what I captured at a different angle with the sun showing between the pier. node.text:
Photo by #CanonExplorerOfLight @atibaphoto: "I have been shooting skate photos for 27 years and moments like this don’t happen often. As a skate photographer, I’m always looking to capture a simple photo showing the essence of skateboarding, but most of the time I’m shooting hand rails and stairs and it’s usually something so gnarly that I have to shoot knowing that I will make the skater look like it’s the gnarliest thing. 

So when we were walking up the street on a normal summer day in downtown LA, I saw the horizon line at the top of the hill with a perfect blown out backlit sky and I was like, that's it. I asked @dashawnjordan to simply push across the street. I didn’t use any flash, I just under exposed by 3 stops. This was shot with EOS R5 and RF70-200mm F2.8 L IS USM. I pushed the lens to 200mm to get the perfect composition so I didn’t lose the wheels. Shutter speed was set to 1/2000 to freeze, ISO 400 and F6.3. What I love about photography is that so often, less is more."

📸 #Canon EOS R5
Lens: RF70-200mm F2.8 L IS USM

node.text:
Photo by #CanonExplorerOfLight @jenwuphoto: "Family and Stars. 

After sunset, summer heat cools, daytime hikers disappear and I hiked alone on a quiet chilly night. Reaching a hilltop, I set up to take photographs of some boulders that I previously scouted to use as the foreground elements. Just then, headlamps beam over the hill as I hear people chatting. I was surprised by the hikers at night but delighted to meet an astronomer viewing the stars with his family. They were friendly so I asked them to pose. I position them as silhouettes to the night sky. I exclaim, 'stay still' and they do. I did some light painting on them but I prefer the silhouettes. I later sent them prints to thank them. I photographed the boulders alone before their arrival - however, my preference is with them included. I like the human element, standing beneath the vast starry sky, with a sense of awe, against the Milky Way! I selected my favorite wide-angle lens for stars as points of light, the EF 24mm f/1.4L II USM. Here it allows the foreground subjects to have tighter coverage in the frame than with wider lenses. I set the shutter speed to 20 seconds and ISO to 1600 to get a good exposure. I am excited to share this image, this month on the cover of @outdoorphotomag with the feature article."

@bobanddawn_inthewild's journey to becoming a #CanonExplorerOfLight: "Dawn and I embrace the saying 'Be First, Be Bold, or Be Forgotten.' We strive to find ways to push the boundaries of our photographs while still keeping true to our brand of timeless, classic moments captured for a lifetime. We are often asked, can I photograph a wedding with you? I'll do anything, carry your bags, set up lights, anything. We came up with a creative approach to this question, Davis Love Story, Real Wedding Workshops, where 15 photographers work alongside us during a real wedding. These weddings are three days of real-world experience. 

Jenni & Steven's rehearsal party was at a classic movie theater in Charleston, South Carolina. 

I thought to myself, if there's a red carpet, there has to be the paparazzi! I had to figure out how can I have all the attending photographers flash fire at the same time? The light bulb went off inside my head, wireless flash! It was 2013, & I used the Canon Speedlite 600EX-RT with built-in radio transmission. At the time, I was the only one using the 600s at the workshop. But, the 600s are backward compatible, using optical, line-of-sight, wireless communication. I knew I could create the photograph I had in mind & before the guests arrived, I explained the vision to the group. I turned the power off on all the cameras, set the Canon Speedlites to receiver mode, all in Optical channel 4, group C, manual flash 1/16th power. I put my Speedlite 600EX-RT to sender, Optical, channel 4, sent the instructions to the remote Speedlites in group C to 1/16th power. The other Speedlites had SU4 mode, an optical receiver that any flash can trigger them to fire. 'Bam,' the test shots worked! The guests began to arrive; we hyped up the energy; cat called the guests, 'who's your designer, what are you wearing?' The idea was a huge success and such a big hit, most guests walked the red carpet twice.

This has taught me to embrace technology, read the manual, and never limit my imagination. I remind myself constantly to be green and growing."

📸 #Canon EOS-1D X
Lens: EF 24-70mm f/2.8L II USM
